Fact #287: Paneling is an important but often overlooked aspect of comic storytelling. The flow of a scene is heavily impacted by how the author makes the reader follow the panels. When it's done well, it's seamless; when it's done poorly, it can feel extremely jarring. Korean webtoons were inherently made to be read online with vertical scrolling, which makes its paneling weaker and far less interesting than Western or Japanese comics.

Fact #280: Yonkoma, or 4koma, is a common comic strip format in Japanese manga often used for gag comedies. They follow a traditional four part composition found in many Chinese, Korean, and Japanese narratives. In Japanese, the first two are Ki (起)and Shou (承) which set the scene and develop it, much like introduction and rising action. The third is the climax, Ten (転), literally the "twist" of the story. Last is the conclusion, Ketsu (結), where the story or joke is concluded-- in other words, the punchline.

Typically, when 4koma manga are adapted into anime, they suffer from finding the right comedic timing. Unlike manga where readers read at their own pace, anime is aired live and there are not pauses between jokes.

Fact #281: Anime is ran at 24 fps, but generally in Japanese anime there is only a new key frame every 3 frames. The other two frames are in-betweens and are not completely new drawings. This is called animating on "Threes". "Twos" are uncommon, but the most fluid animation run on "Ones": 24 distinct new drawings per second. This is usually what most sakuga is made up of because of its impressiveness to animate even a 15 second cut on "Ones" would take a stupidly large amount of time. Converting a scene to 60 fps adds in automatically generated extra frames which is actually detrimental to the overall movement of a cut and is an insanely retarded idea.
